name: Winner of architecture prize
summary: The apartment lets you experience one of the hippest new areas of Berlin at the same time as experiencing a space that is unique in its layout. Living in this architecture is an experience that introduces new perspectives of spatial conversions.
space: The apartment is done as an art project together with an architect and was awarded by the Architecture Prize Berlin 2013 because of its experimental use of space. The space creates new perspectives of living spaces and is a amazing experience on its own, together with all that Berlin has to offer. The different levels creates situations where small intimate spheres and large space goes in dialogue, and the modes that the space creates can be changed based on the situation. For kids it´s a gigantic playground, and for larger groups of people it creates rooms within the rooms.  The apartment is just a 7 minute walk from Hermannplatz, which connects you to the Airport in 30 minutes, to Mitte in 10 minutes, and Charlottenburg in 15. The apartment in total consists of 2 bedrooms (each 22,5 m2), a balcony (4m2), and the large room (45 m2), with the kitchen, the bathroom box and the podium with living room/yellow workspace/french balcony. neighborhood_overview: Kreuzkölln is the new very trendy area with lots of bars, restaurants and cultural events right outside the door, so you don´t even need to move to get a real shot of the Berlin feel. The street is very lively and there are cafées, bars and new project spaces opening every month in this district. Also you can find cosy ice cream parlors, great turkish food, Japanese ramen, the best place for Burgers in Kreuzberg, and also the place known for 20 years for serving the best French croissants right outside the doorstep. The area has gone through a very fast gentrification and the street is filled with very popular bars and restaurants. This is perfect for having access to good food right outside the door, but also in the night the street can be a little bit loud, as the pulse of the city streams into the apartment. The bed facing the backyard, the one on the podium, is more quiet and makes it possible to shut of the street life.
transit: The U7 and U8 from Hermannplatz takes you in all kind of directions in the city. Hermannplatz is 7 min walk from the apartment, along the cozy Weserstrasse, also filled with nice bars and cafés. There are also busses within 2 min walk from the apartment that takes you in almost any direction in the city.
access: Guests have access to the large bedroom. This is the room with the  entrance to the balcony and that partly has a floating structure of the same material as the podium on parts of the floor. The room with the chandelier on the pictures I use as my bedroom/studio when I have guests. The guests then have private acccess to their own bedroom, the bathroom, the balcony and the main room with the kitchen/podium. I close off the room with the chandelier as my private living/workspace.
interaction: I work a lot, so I sit a lot in my studio, but I also am a very social person, so we might see eachother little or more depending on my timeschedule. I am always willing to give tips about Berlin if the guests need it.
house_rules: The apartment is a unique project and is very dear to me, and it is represented in architect magazines and competitions, so it is important that anyone staying here with me conciders the house rules and takes good care of the place. The place is suitable as a silent retreat from the city, rather than a place for a party. The material that the podium is made of is a bit vulnerable and very expensive to replace, it can´t have water lying on it for a long time without getting damaged, it is not heat proof like concrete is, and gets scratches if furniture is moved over it with sharp edges. But using the apartment with a careful touch just gets you in even closer contact with the architecture, enjoy!
host_about:
I am a female artist from Norway, that works between Oslo, Stockholm and Berlin. I travel a lot, and rent out my apartment in Berlin while I am gone. 
I have spent so many years traveling from place to place and living in different spaces, so I am used to the life in a suitcase, and it´s easy for me to find a home in new spaces and with new people. Also my place in Berlin is designed in a very neutral way to make space for whatever room you need for what you are working on, your thoughts, or whatever social setting you are within at the certain moment.

I am also renting out my parents property on the Algarve coast of Portugal.
